 the reparation of victims’ past injuries, dealing with the former regime, and institutional reform. Women, civil society, and tribes, among other social forces, can support the transition process. Fraihat’s research shows how some aspects of transitions have been politicized and that each country has taken a specific approach, raising or diminishing the chances of civil war or a healthy transition. This book is based on the original field research Fraihat conducted over three years in Yemen, Libya, and Tunisia. It is the result of over 200 interviews with key figures including senior government officials, heads of political parties, revolutionary youth activists, former regime loyalists, representatives of women’s and civil society organizations, military and militia commanders, tribal leaders, and members of displaced communities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aArab Spring, 2010-. 0aDemocratizationzArab countries. 0aDemocratizationzLibya. 0aDemocratizationzTunisia. 0aDemocratizationzYemen (Republic). 0aPeace-buildingzArab countries. 0aPeace-buildingzLibya. 0aPeace-buildingzTunisia. 0aPeace-buildingzYemen (Republic). 0aReconciliationxPolitical aspectszArab countries. 0aReconciliationxPolitical aspectszLibya. 0aReconciliationxPolitical aspectszTunisia. 0aReconciliationxPolitical aspectszYemen (Republic). 0aRevolutionszArab countries. 0aRevolutionszLibya. 0aRevolutionszTunisia. 0aRevolutionszYemen (Republic). 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066771440uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030022095740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300220957423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300220957/original  a978-3-11-066771-4  Yale Univer